[While cattle remain the primary source for EHEC, usually by contaminated ground beef, by soiling of irrigation water or direct exposure to the animal or its environment, this proposed vehicle for transmission is unusual. However, it shouldn't be unexpected since "green" tripe is raw, unwashed, unbleached, unscalded stomach tissue which can contain both the muscular and mucosal layers (the latter of which is often stained green and/or brown from vegetation eaten by the cows, hence the name). As such "green" tripe may be the source of virtually any bovine gastrointestinal pathogen and an excellent means with which to infect other susceptible species.

Green tripe differs from traditional beef tripe for human consumption (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tripe) which is made from only the muscle wall (the interior mucosal lining is removed) of only the first 3 chambers of a cow's stomach: the rumen (blanket/flat/smooth tripe), the reticulum (honeycomb and pocket tripe), and the omasum (book/bible/leaf tripe). Abomasum (reed) tripe is seen less frequently, owing to its glandular tissue content. Tripe typically refers to cow (beef) stomach but includes stomach of any ruminant, including cattle, sheep, deer, antelope, giraffes, and their relatives. Tripas, the related Spanish word, also refers to culinary dishes produced from any animal with a stomach. In some cases, other names have been applied to the "tripe" of other animals. For example, tripe from pigs may be referred to as paunch, or hog maw. Tripe is eaten in many parts of the world. Tripe soup is made in many varieties in the Eastern European cuisine. Tripe dishes eaten by humans include andouille (French poached, boiled and smoked cold tripe sausage) and breakfast sausages (most commercially produced sausages in the US contain pork and beef tripe as filler). While tripe can be made safe to eat via washing, bleaching, scalding, removing the mucosal layer, etc. it is clearly not without risk especially when the aforementioned steps are skipped and/or cross-contamination occurs during the cleaning/disinfection of the muscular portion of the stomachs.

It is not stated in the post if the affected individuals received antimicrobials early in their illnesses, which can increase the risk of HUS. Fatalities from EHEC infection generally occur when central nervous symptoms occur during HUS. - Mods.LL/JH

